hook.real_world_problem:
Meet the two most common production bugs in Java:

**Bug 1 — NullPointerException in the middle of logic:**
```java
public double calculateDiscount(Order order) {
    // 300 lines later...
    return order.getCustomer().getLoyaltyLevel().getDiscountRate(); // NPE!
    // Which one is null? No idea. Stack trace is 12 frames deep.
}
```

**Bug 2 — Silent corruption from shared mutable state:**
```java
public class Order {
    private List<Item> items;
    public Order(List<Item> items) {
        this.items = items;  // BUG: stored reference to caller's list!
    }
}
// Caller then modifies their list... and the order's items change too.
```

Both bugs are preventable with defensive programming:

**Fix 1 — Fail at the entry point:**
```java
public double calculateDiscount(Order order) {
    Objects.requireNonNull(order, "order must not be null");
    Objects.requireNonNull(order.getCustomer(), "order must have a customer");
    // Now you get a clear NPE with a message at the TOP, not buried in logic
    return order.getCustomer().getLoyaltyLevel().getDiscountRate();
}
```

**Fix 2 — Defensive copy:**
```java
public Order(List<Item> items) {
    Objects.requireNonNull(items, "items must not be null");
    this.items = new ArrayList<>(items);  // defensive copy — we own our data
}
```

Defensive programming is about catching problems at boundaries — the moment data enters your code — not hoping they don't cause damage later.

concept_explanation.fail_fast_principle:
**Fail fast** — detect and report problems as early as possible.

The opposite is 'fail slow': accept bad input, pass it around, and crash mysteriously somewhere deep in your code hours or days later.

```java
// FAIL SLOW — bad input travels far:
public void processUser(User user) {
    // No validation...
    String email = user.getEmail();
    sendConfirmation(email);  // NPE here — but user came from 10 layers up
    saveToDatabase(user);     // IllegalArgumentException here — from somewhere else
}

// FAIL FAST — problem caught immediately:
public void processUser(User user) {
    Objects.requireNonNull(user, "user must not be null");
    if (user.getEmail() == null || user.getEmail().isBlank()) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("user email is required");
    }
    // Everything after here: guaranteed valid user with email
    sendConfirmation(user.getEmail());
    saveToDatabase(user);
}
```

**Why fail fast wins**:
- NullPointerException at line 2 (your validation) vs line 47 (somewhere in logic)
- Clear error message: 'user email is required' vs 'NullPointerException'
- Problem is at the ENTRY POINT where you can see which caller passed bad data
- Subsequent code is simpler: no defensive null checks throughout

concept_explanation.objects_requirenonnull:
**`Objects.requireNonNull()`** — the standard Java way to reject null:

```java
import java.util.Objects;

public class PaymentService {
    private final BankClient bank;

    public PaymentService(BankClient bank) {
        // Fail if someone constructs this with null:
        this.bank = Objects.requireNonNull(bank, "bank client must not be null");
    }

    public void transfer(String from, String to, double amount) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(from, "source account id required");
        Objects.requireNonNull(to, "destination account id required");
        // ... safe to use from and to here
    }
}
```

`Objects.requireNonNull(value, message)` returns the value if non-null, or throws `NullPointerException` with your message if null.

**Inline assignment pattern** — use in constructors and setters:
```java
this.bank = Objects.requireNonNull(bank, "bank must not be null");
// Equivalent to:
if (bank == null) throw new NullPointerException("bank must not be null");
this.bank = bank;
```

**When to use it**:
- Constructor parameters that must not be null
- Method parameters where null would cause problems downstream
- Before storing a reference in a field

**Note**: `Objects.requireNonNull` throws `NullPointerException`. For public APIs where null is genuinely an invalid argument (not just missing), you might prefer `IllegalArgumentException` — more semantically clear. Both are fine; teams choose one convention and stick to it.

concept_explanation.guard_clauses:
**Guard clauses** — validate at the TOP of a method, return or throw early:

```java
// WITHOUT guard clauses — deeply nested:
public String processOrder(Order order, User user) {
    if (order != null) {
        if (user != null) {
            if (order.getItems() != null && !order.getItems().isEmpty()) {
                if (user.isActive()) {
                    // actual logic buried here
                    return doProcess(order, user);
                } else {
                    return "User inactive";
                }
            } else {
                return "Empty order";
            }
        } else {
            return "No user";
        }
    } else {
        return "No order";
    }
}
```

```java
// WITH guard clauses — flat and readable:
public String processOrder(Order order, User user) {
    if (order == null)                             return "No order";
    if (user == null)                              return "No user";
    if (order.getItems() == null || order.getItems().isEmpty()) return "Empty order";
    if (!user.isActive())                          return "User inactive";

    // actual logic — no nesting:
    return doProcess(order, user);
}
```

Guard clauses:
- Check INVALID conditions and return/throw early
- Leave the main logic unindented and readable
- Each guard expresses exactly ONE validation concern
- After all guards pass: guaranteed all preconditions are met

concept_explanation.defensive_copies:
**Defensive copies** — protect your state from external mutation:

**On input (constructor/setter):**
```java
public class Exam {
    private final List<String> questions;

    public Exam(List<String> questions) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(questions, "questions required");
        // Defensive copy — we own our version:
        this.questions = new ArrayList<>(questions);
    }
    // Now caller can modify their list — Exam is unaffected
}
```

**On output (getter):**
```java
public List<String> getQuestions() {
    return Collections.unmodifiableList(questions);
    // Or: return new ArrayList<>(questions);
}
// Caller can't modify the returned list to affect internal state
```

**On dates (Date is mutable — avoid in modern Java, but common in legacy):**
```java
public Date getDeadline() {
    return new Date(deadline.getTime());  // copy — not the internal object
}
```

**When to make defensive copies**:
- Constructor receives a mutable collection/array/Date: copy it
- Getter returns a mutable internal field: return unmodifiable view or copy
- No need for primitive types (int, double) — they're immutable by nature
- Strings are immutable — no copy needed

**The rule**: If you store someone else's mutable object, you own a copy. If you return your mutable internal object, return a copy or view.

concept_explanation.precondition_pattern:
**Preconditions** — explicit contracts at the start of a method:

```java
public double calculateEmi(double principal, double annualRate, int months) {
    // State what THIS METHOD requires — its contract:
    if (principal <= 0) 
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("principal must be positive, got: " + principal);
    if (annualRate < 0)
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("annualRate cannot be negative, got: " + annualRate);
    if (months <= 0)
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("months must be positive, got: " + months);

    // Contract established — safe to compute:
    double r = annualRate / 12 / 100;
    if (r == 0) return principal / months;
    double pow = Math.pow(1 + r, months);
    return principal * r * pow / (pow - 1);
}
```

**Guava's Preconditions class** (widely used in production):
```java
import com.google.common.base.Preconditions;

Preconditions.checkNotNull(user, "user required");
Preconditions.checkArgument(age >= 0, "age must be non-negative, got %s", age);
Preconditions.checkState(!isProcessed, "order already processed");
```

You won't always have Guava, but recognizing the pattern matters. In standard Java, use `Objects.requireNonNull` for null checks and `if + throw IllegalArgumentException` for value checks.

concept_explanation.immutable_design:
**Immutable objects — the ultimate defense:**

An immutable object cannot change after creation — no defensive copies needed, no unexpected mutation.

```java
// Mutable — requires defensive copies everywhere:
class MutablePoint {
    int x, y;
    void setX(int x) { this.x = x; }
    void setY(int y) { this.y = y; }
}

// Immutable — safe to share, no copying needed:
final class Point {  // final prevents subclassing
    private final int x, y;  // final fields

    public Point(int x, int y) { this.x = x; this.y = y; }

    public int getX() { return x; }  // no setters
    public int getY() { return y; }

    // Instead of mutation, return a NEW object:
    public Point translate(int dx, int dy) { return new Point(x + dx, y + dy); }

    @Override public String toString() { return "(" + x + "," + y + ")"; }
}
```

**Rules for immutable classes**:
1. All fields `final`
2. No setters
3. Class `final` (prevent subclass from breaking immutability)
4. If fields are mutable types (List, Date), make defensive copies in constructor and getters

`String`, `Integer`, `LocalDate` — Java's most-used immutable types.

Immutable objects are automatically thread-safe, free of aliasing bugs, easy to reason about.

concept_explanation.null_return_values:
**Avoiding null as a return value** — the root cause of most NPEs:

**Problem**: returning null when 'nothing found':
```java
public User findUserById(int id) {
    return map.get(id);  // returns null if not found
}

// Caller forgets null check:
String email = findUserById(42).getEmail();  // NPE if not found!
```

**Solution 1: Return Optional** (Java 8+):
```java
public Optional<User> findUserById(int id) {
    return Optional.ofNullable(map.get(id));
}

// Caller must handle the 'not found' case:
Optional<User> user = findUserById(42);
if (user.isPresent()) {
    System.out.println(user.get().getEmail());
}
// Or:
String email = findUserById(42)
    .map(User::getEmail)
    .orElse("unknown");  // safe default
```

**Solution 2: Throw exception** (when absence is an error):
```java
public User findUserById(int id) {
    User user = map.get(id);
    if (user == null) throw new UserNotFoundException("User " + id + " not found");
    return user;  // guaranteed non-null
}
```

**When to use which**:
- User might reasonably not exist (search result) → `Optional<User>`
- User MUST exist (this is an error state) → throw exception
- Internal-only method where caller knows it's valid → can return null (but document it)

Optional will be covered in detail in Module 9 (Streams). For now: know it exists, understand `isPresent()`, `get()`, `orElse()`.

concept_explanation.validation_boundary:
**The validation boundary** — WHERE to validate:

```
[External world] ──→ [YOUR BOUNDARY] ──→ [Internal logic]
    Untrusted input  ↑                        Trusted data
                     Validate HERE
```

**Public methods** = boundary. Validate all inputs.
**Private methods** = internal. Trust the caller (usually you). Validate as documentation/safety.

```java
public class OrderService {
    // PUBLIC boundary — validate everything:
    public Order placeOrder(String customerId, List<Item> items) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(customerId, "customerId required");
        Objects.requireNonNull(items, "items required");
        if (items.isEmpty()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("order must have items");

        return processValidatedOrder(customerId, new ArrayList<>(items));
    }

    // PRIVATE internal — can trust inputs are valid:
    private Order processValidatedOrder(String customerId, List<Item> items) {
        // No need to re-validate — caller (placeOrder) guaranteed validity
        // Still guard against truly impossible states with assert if desired
    }
}
```

Don't over-validate. Private methods called only by your own validated public methods don't need the full validation dance. Focus your defensive energy at the BOUNDARY where external data enters.

