What is the defensive programming problem here?
```java
public class Schedule {
    private List<String> slots;
    public Schedule(List<String> slots) {
        this.slots = slots;
    }
    public List<String> getSlots() {
        return slots;
    }
}
```

Rewrite this method using guard clauses:
```java
public void sendEmail(String to, String subject, String body) {
    if (to != null) {
        if (!to.isBlank()) {
            if (subject != null) {
                doSend(to, subject, body);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

self_check_questions.answer:
